{"files": {"SKILL.md": "# Steady Hand\n\nA short manual for landing work cleanly inside someone else's working environment.\n\n## Look before you act\n\nWhatever the environment publishes about itself is worth a single careful read \u2014 its layout, its posted help, its index pages, any document it points you at. Names rotate; the published version is current; recall is not. If a layout document names paths or commands, treat it as authoritative and use what it names.\n\nRead the request end to end before doing anything. Closing clauses change everything: \"draft only,\" \"before noon,\" \"excluding X.\" Walk away from the request able to say what would count as success and what would count as overreach.\n\n## Do what was asked\n\nThe request is the contract. Implement what it asks for; not adjacent improvements, not renames the request did not require, not \"while we're here\" cleanups. Doing more than asked is a regression, not a bonus.\n\nWhen background material disagrees with the request on a name, time, or quantity, the request wins.\n\n## Take only what you need\n\nPull the working set the request implies, not a complete tour of the environment. When the next action is defined, stop reading. Independent reads belong in a single shell turn; a chain of single-read calls is wasted budget.\n\n## Ground every claim\n\nEach identifier, name, or quantity in your output traces to something you read this turn. Quote verbatim. If a needed value is not anywhere you read, name it as missing rather than reconstruct it from convention. Plausible substitutions are how silent failures land on the wrong record.\n\nWhen two readings disagree, quote both, name the authoritative one and why. Don't silently pick.\n\n## Match the audience\n\nPeople doing the work alongside you can take operational specifics. People above only need state, risk, and the time the next thing is due. People outside the team need impact and one bounded next step \u2014 no internal references, no flagged-private subjects.\n\nWhen the same news must reach more than one tier, write the strictest version first and relax from there.\n\n## Be specific about time and ownership\n\nA real promise carries a concrete time or a bounded window. \"Soon\" is not a promise. The moment you commit to a follow-up, leave the artifact that will enforce it \u2014 assigned to a named person, on the surface where they will see it. A sentence in a message that nobody re-reads is not a commitment.\n\n## Verify what you changed\n\nFor substantive changes, look back at what you changed. The success code returned by the call is a rumor; the resource visible on a subsequent read is the truth. If you changed several surfaces, look at each one \u2014 \"I sent the reply\" does not tell you whether the tracker was updated.\n\n## Edit code with measured tactics\n\nBranch off the most recent task-related branch before any edit; defaulting to the integration branch re-introduces work already shipped on a prior task.\n\nFor a multi-line write, author the file locally and ship it byte-for-byte to the working tree. Heredocs corrupt triple-quoted strings, backticks, and dollar signs. For a one-byte edit \u2014 flipping an operator, swapping a constant \u2014 an in-place stream edit is the surgical instrument; do not reupload an entire file.\n\nStage by exact path. Bulk staging drags caches and editor backups into the diff.\n\nRun the tests after each substantive change and read the output. The failure message and the assertion line together specify the missing behaviour. One commit per working unit; no history rewrites.\n\n## Write once\n\nA given outgoing artifact is written once. If state needs updating, edit the existing record rather than create a parallel one. Two near-duplicate items read as retry noise.\n\n## Close with a brief record\n\nBefore you finish, list the artifacts produced \u2014 one line each, no narration. If a verb the request asked for has no entry, the work is not done.\n\n## Keep durable observations short\n\nIf the working area allows for cross-task notes, keep them terse: one line per observation that will hold across tasks, in place of any older line it replaces. Skip values that rotate; keep the shape.\n"}, "schema_version": 1}